Mozambique, located in southeastern Africa along the Indian Ocean, generally has a tropical climate characterized by distinct wet and dry seasons.

The wet season typically runs from November to April, with heavy rainfall, particularly from January to March. Temperatures during this period are warm and humid, ranging from the 70s to 90s Fahrenheit (around 21-32°C).

The dry season occurs from May to October, with little to no rainfall and cooler temperatures. Daytime temperatures during the dry season can still be quite warm, ranging from the 70s to 80s Fahrenheit (around 21-30°C), but nights may be cooler.

Coastal areas tend to be more humid, while inland regions may experience more variation in temperature due to elevation.

It's worth noting that Mozambique is susceptible to tropical cyclones, especially along the coast, particularly during the wet season. These cyclones can bring heavy rainfall, strong winds, and storm surges, so travelers should be aware of the potential risks and monitor weather updates if visiting during the wet season.